[[File:Shang dynasty forms of the Chinese character 皇 (Huang).jpg|thumb|300px|{{w|Shang dynasty}} forms of {{m|zh|皇}}.]]

{{liushu|p}} — variously analysed as a radiant feather headdress (as worn in the {{zh-l|皇舞}}, a ritual dance for celestial worship; a blooming flower (original form of {{och-l|葟|tr=*wˤaŋ}}, or a blazing flame (original form of {{och-l|煌|tr=*wˤaŋ}}). These share a common visual motif of outward radiance — rays or petals emanating from a centre — also reflected in the derivative {{och-l|凰|phoenix|tr=*wˤaŋ}}.

Later evolved into {{Han compound|𤼽|王|ls=psc|c1=s|c2=p|nocap=y|tr=*wˤaŋ|tr2=*waŋ}}.

===Etymology===
{{zh-ref|Bodman (1980)}} proposes a connection with {{och-l|王|tr=*ɢʷaŋ}} "king" (see there for more information).

